# makes plots nice
def make_pretty(ax, title='', x_label='', y_label='', img=False):
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=20)
    ax.set_xlabel(x_label, fontsize=16)
    ax.set_ylabel(y_label, fontsize=16)
    ax.legend(loc='best', fontsize=16)
    if img:
        ax.axis('off')
    return ax

def make_hist(ax, col, df):
    print(f'Min of {col}: {df[col].min()}')
    print(f'Max of {col}: {df[col].max()}')
    ax = df[col].plot(kind='hist', ax=ax)
    make_pretty(ax, f'{col} Histogram', col, 'Frequency')

def make_bar(ax, col, df):
    vc = df[col].value_counts()
    
    ax = vc.plot(kind='bar', ax=ax)
    make_pretty(ax, col, f'{col} labels', f'{col} value counts')
    return ax

A rideshare company is interested in predicting rider retention. You are provided a sample dataset of a cohort of users who signed up for an account in January 2014. The data was collected on July 1, 2014, and it consits of the following columns:

Data description¶

  • city: city this user signed up in
  • phone: primary device for this user
  • signup_date: date of account registration; in the form ‘YYYYMMDD’
  • last_trip_date: the last time this user completed a trip; in the form ‘YYYYMMDD’
  • avg_dist: the average distance in miles per trip taken in the first 30 days after signup
  • avg_rating_by_driver: the rider’s average rating over all of their trips
  • avg_rating_of_driver: the rider’s average rating of their drivers over all of their trips
  • surge_pct: the percent of trips taken with surge multiplier > 1
  • avg_surge: The average surge multiplier over all of this user’s trips
  • trips_in_first_30_days: the number of trips this user took in the first 30 days after signing up
  • premium_ride_service: TRUE if the user requested a premium ride service in their first 30 days; FALSE otherwise
  • weekday_pct: the percent of the user’s trips occurring during a weekday

We consider a user retained if they were “active” (i.e. took a trip) in the last 30 days preceding July 1, 2014. We would like you to use this data set to help understand what factors are the best predictors for retention.

  1. Perform any cleaning, exploratory analysis, and/or visualizations to use the provided data for this analysis. What fraction of the observed users were retained/active?

  2. Build a predictive model that can predict whether or not a user will be active in their 6th month on the system. Explain your experimental setup and what evaluation metric you choosed.

  3. Briefly discuss the insights gained from the model.

Pipe work¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.preprocessing import FunctionTransformer
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

num_attribs = ['trips_in_first_30_days', 'avg_rating_of_driver', 'avg_surge', 'surge_pct', 'weekday_pct', 'avg_dist', 'avg_rating_by_driver']
cat_attribs = ['city', 'premium_ride_service', 'phone']

def extract_date_time_signup(X):
    X = X.copy()

    X['signup_date_month'] = X['signup_date'].dt.month
    X['signup_date_day'] = X['signup_date'].dt.day
    return X[['signup_date_month', 'signup_date_day']]







num_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
    ('std_scaler', StandardScaler())
])

full_pipe = Pipeline([
    ('preprocessor', ColumnTransformer([
        ('num', num_pipeline, num_attribs),
        ('date', FunctionTransformer(extract_date_time_signup), ['signup_date']),
        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(), cat_attribs)
    ]))
])


features = full_pipe.fit_transform(X_train)
